40|$|Submitted in partial {{fulfillment}} of the requirements for the Degree of Master of Business Administration at Strathmore UniversityThe study seeks to test the relationship between corporate employee disclosures and financial performance of the organization. In the recent {{years there has been}} a lot of dissatisfaction with stakeholders relying on mandatory financial disclosures in decision making. Many governing bodies as well as professional bodies have advocated for additional voluntary disclosures in the company’s annual reports. Listed companies are seen to disclose <b>additional</b> <b>voluntary</b> <b>information</b> in order to raise cheap source of capital. An organization that discloses additional information is seen to reduce the level of uncertainty and in turn is able to attract low cost capital from investors. Voluntary disclosures were supported in the study by two major theories that is Agency theory and Legitimacy theory. Most of the prior studies done have focused on the determinants of voluntary disclosures with a few linking the voluntary disclosures with the cost of capital. This study focused on the relationship between corporate employee disclosures and the firm’s financial performance. Employee disclosures were chosen because employees are a key resource to the organization and have an impact on the organization’s bottom line. The study utilized correlational study research design targeting 67 listed companies in the Nairobi Stock Exchange. A sample size of 47 listed companies was chosen for the study. The unit of analysis was the companies. Secondary data was sourced from the companies’ annual reports while the stock performance information was picked from the Nairobi Stock Exchange website and companies’ websites. The data was collected for a period of three years i. e. 2013, 2014 and 2015. The study utilized a multivariate model of analysis. The results of the study revealed that there was a positive and significant relationship between employee disclosures and financial performance of the listed companies. The disclosures varied across industries with the telecommunication and technology industry had the highest level of disclosures. The study contributes to the literature on the demand for employee disclosure as a determinant of financial performance in developing countries. It identifies the level of employee disclosure practices among listed companies in NSE. Moreover, it reveals significant differences among industry sectors. The authors theorized that in developing countries, legitimacy and agency theory have forced companies to embrace voluntary disclosure in order to enhance financial performance. The study was limited in terms of time, disclosures varied across companies and years and the possibility of the independent and dependent variables being measured by more than one variable...|$|E
