40|$|The {{main purpose}} of this paper is to examine the cost {{constraints}} on <b>voluntary</b> <b>information</b> disclosure in a comparative study of the perceptions of financial executives in U. K. and U. S. multinationals. The study examines the perceived net costs or benefits of disclosing information voluntarily, the types of costs involved and the significance of cost constraints in respect of specific items of disclosure. The results suggest that while there is substantial agreement on the major cost constraints involved and the individual items giving rise to major net costs, there are significantly different perceptions by U. K. and U. S. financial executives in terms of the overall emphasis of responses to the issue of cost constraints on <b>voluntary</b> <b>information</b> disclosures. © 1990 JIBS. Journal of International Business Studies (1990) 21, 597 – 622...|$|R
